ariants":[{"name":"Bricken","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeen): probably a variant of   Brechin  .","Americanized form of German <b>Brücken</b>, a cognate of   Bruck  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David de Brechin was born after 1271, in Brechin, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, William Brechin, was 8762 and his mother, Elena Comyn, was 8756. He married Lady Margaret de Bonkyl about 1285, in Lanarkshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 4 August 1320, in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Aft 1271–Aft 4 August 1320":"pärast 1271–pärast 4. augustit 1320","1271–1320":"1271–1320","1249–1304":"1249–1304","1303–1351":"1303–1351","1237–1292":"1237–1292","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","3 October 1304":"3. oktoober 1304","Aft 4 August 1320":"pärast 4. augustit 1320","1242":"1242","1351":"1351","1271":"1271","1292":"1292","10 Dec 1292":"10. detsember 1292","1304":"1304","1249":"1249","1303":"1303","1237":"1237","1320":"1320","Aft 1271":"pärast 1271","about 1299":"umbes 1285","Lanarks